420":"1420","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1395":"1395","1419":"1419","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Kingston upon Hull, East Riding district, Yorkshire, England, UnIted Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Church of Saint Mary, Lowgate, Kingston upon Hull, East Riding, Yorkshire, England, UnIted Kingdom":"Cleveland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Trollope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Troughburn in Hethpool (Northumberland), which was formerly known as <i>Trollop</i>. The old placename appears to derive from Old Norse <i>troll</i> ‘troll, supernatural being’ + Old English <i>hop</i> ‘small enclosed valley’.","History: An English family of this name trace their descent from John Trowlope, who lived at Thornlaw (Durham) in the late 14th century. One of his descendants was the novelist Anthony Trollope (1815–82)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tulip","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): probably a late variant of   Trollope  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Trollope was born in 1400, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Trollope, was 30 and her mother, Mrs. Thomas Trollope, was 20. She married Edmond Swyfte in 1418, in Durham, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1400–Deceased":"1400–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1395–1419":"1395–1419","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1414–1454":"1414–1454","1420–1485":"1420–1485","1430–1510":"1430–1510","1370–1399":"1370–1399","1380–1399":"1380–1399","1414":"1414","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1399":"1399","1454":"1454","1420":"